id="post-4439" class="post-4439 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-direct-action category-energy category-environment tag-activists tag-chile tag-dam"><h1 class="entry-title entry-title-single">Chilean Dam Project Broken Up Thanks to Activists and Locals</h1><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2014/06/16 9:31 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/06/16/chilean-dam-project-broken-up-thanks-to-activists-and-locals/" title="Chilean Dam Project Broken Up Thanks to Activists and Locals" rel="bookmark">2014/06/16 9:31 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="comments-link"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/06/16/chilean-dam-project-broken-up-thanks-to-activists-and-locals/#comments">Leave a Comment</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Activism works, just ask the Chilean communities that stopped a hydroelectric dam from being built. The dam was going to cause a lot of local ecological havoc with little actual gain to the local populace. The Chilean government has backed down from building the dam and the communities that were to be affected are celebrating the decision. Chile is committed to supporting other forms of renewable energy that won&#8217;t cause such environmental damage.</p><blockquote><p>The committee &#8220;decided to side with complaints presented by the community,&#8221; Environment Minister Pablo Badenier told reporters. &#8220;As of now, the hydroelectric project has been rejected.&#8221;<br
/> &#8230;<br
/> Opponents complained that the plan required 5,700 hectares (14,000 acres) of land to be submerged and would involve cutting through swathes of forests to build the dams along the Baker and Pascua rivers. Fears were also expressed that the project, which would have involved the relocation of some three dozen families, would destroy vital habitat for the endangered Southern Huemul deer.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.dw.de/chile-rejects-patagonia-wilderness-dam-project/a-17698908">Read more.</a></p><div
